{"type":"message","id":"bf482587","parentId":"d4e6081c","timestamp":"2026-03-10T06:02:18.353Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"**Agent Subagent Capabilities:**\n\n**All 6 agents can spawn subagents** - this is a core Kurultai capability. Each agent has:\n- Access to `sessions_spawn()` for parallel execution\n- Subagent orchestration via `subagents` tool\n- Independent workspace for task execution\n\n**However, the current execution model differs by task type:**\n\n| Task Type | Execution Method |\n|-----------|-----------------|\n| **Human-routed tasks** | Subprocess via `claude-agent` (not ACP) |\n| **Agent self-spawned work** | ACP sessions via `sessions_spawn()` |\n\n**Why the difference:**\n- Subprocess: Scale efficiency, no session registry pollution, PID-based tracking\n- ACP sessions: Cross-agent collaboration, model switching, short-lived subagent work\n\n**Current Issue:**\nThe task-watcher daemon that processes `.md` task files uses subprocess execution. If it's not running or is blocked, tasks queue but don't execute. This is what jochi is investigating.\n\n**Parallelism within a single agent:**\n- Each agent can spawn multiple subagents for parallel work\n- But the main task queue (filesystem-based) processes one task at a time per agent via task-watcher\n\nDoes this clarify the architecture?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"bailian","model":"kimi-k2.5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773122524547}}
